<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude" id="rei-materia" lang="en" >
    <head>EAGLE/EpiDoc Material Vocabulary</head>
    <ab>
        <rs type="conformance">aiegl</rs>
    </ab>
    <p>The EpiDoc community is collaborating to produce a standard, multilingual vocabulary
        to describe and classify the material of the monuments and objects bearing inscribed texts.
        This effort is being coordinated with the direction of the EAGLE constituent databases
        to ensure compatibilty for EAGLE-conformant EpiDoc. For tagging guidance, see <xref href="description-material.xml">Describing the material of the inscribed object</xref> 
    </p>
    <p>The current draft version of the full vocabulary is maintained in a GoogleDoc spreadsheet
    for ready access by all collaborators. The following list of keys and English terms is provided here only
    for example. Parties who wish to review or contribute to the full vocabulary should
    enquire on the Markup List.</p>
    
    
    <list type="definition">
        <item>EAGLE term (Latin, used in "key" attribute on <tag>rs type="material"</tag>) = English term</item>
        <item>aes = bronze</item>
        <item>arenatum = fresh mortar</item>
        <item>argentum = silver</item>
        <item>aurum = gold</item>
        <item>cera	 = wax</item>
        <item>creta = terracotta</item>
        <item>ferrum = iron</item>
        <item>lapis = stone</item>
        <item>lignum = wood</item>
        <item>marmor = marble</item>
        <item>musivum = mosaic</item>
        <item>plumbum = lead</item>
        <item>tectorium = stucco</item>
        <item>vitrum = glass</item>
        
    </list>
    
